  "prompt": "How do I identify and differentiate a Ghazal and a Hindi Kavita (poem)?",
  "response": "Here's how you can identify and differentiate a Ghazal and a Hindi Kavita:\n\nGhazal Characteristics:\n1. Originated in Arabic and Persian poetry\n2. Consists of couplets (shers)\n3. Each couplet is independent yet connected thematically\n4. Follows strict metrical patterns\n5. Usually deals with love, separation, and philosophical themes\n6. Typically has a rhyming pattern (qafia)\n7. Often includes the poet's name in the last couplet (takhallus)\n8. Written in Urdu or Persian language\n9. Musically renderable\n10. Strict structural rules\n\nHindi Kavita Characteristics:\n1. Originated in Indian literary traditions\n2. Can have multiple stanzas/verses\n3. More flexible in structure\n4. Less rigid metrical requirements\n5. Covers wide range of themes\n6. Can be written in free verse or specific formats\n7. Uses Hindi language\n8. More contemporary and experimental\n9. Focuses on emotional expression\n10. Less musical constraints\n\nKey Differences:\n- Language\n- Structural rigidity\n- Thematic approach\n- Musical adaptability\n\nUnderstanding these distinctions helps in identifying and appreciating each form's unique characteristics.",
